s to the early days of the web when users could freely surf with anonymity morozov concludes that facebook and google have replaced this era of freedom with one dominated by the voyeurism of the crowd and driven by advertizing dollars morozov cautions that the new concept of frictionless sharing from the articles we read to the movies we watch has comprised our freedom to surf html+ read more the new york times the death of the cyberflaneur http www nytimes com 2012 02 05 o search cddrl search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages news of interest where are the women in the huffington post how web 2.0 drives political change in the arab world and beyond march 9 2011 program on liberation technology news mcfaul part of carnegie endowment panel on russia's over managed democracy may 18 2008 news us saudi relations remain intimate despite differences over iran and arab israeli issue says cddrl visiting professor teitelbaum in the news tel aviv notes on september 25 2007 russia's revolution is not over michael a mcfaul christian science monitor on september 20 1999 forget about monica it's moscow and the stakes are global michael a mcfaul los angeles times on august 14 1998 support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4610 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
